# methods to reverse the words in hebrew so we can read them correctly
def reverse(string): 
    string = "".join(reversed(string)) 
    return string 
def dffeaturesReverse(df): 
    features=[]
    for i in df.columns:
        features.append(reverse(i))
    df.columns = features
    return df

# we check if the ratio is more the the "Raf". if yes meaning we need suppervision else we dont need
def ChecksuperviseNeeded(df):
    superviseNeeded=[]
    for votes, pasol in zip(df["מצביעים"],df["פסולים"]) :
        if pasol / votes > 0.005:
            superviseNeeded.append(1)
        else:
            superviseNeeded.append(0) 
    return superviseNeeded

# calcuatin each settlment his ratio between voters and invalid votes.
def calculateRatio(df):
    finalRatio = []
    for votes, Hizoypasol in zip(df["מצביעים"],df["פסולים"]) :
        finalRatio.append(Hizoypasol / math.sqrt(votes))
    df["יחס סופי"] = finalRatio
    df = df.sort_values(by=['יחס סופי'], ascending = False)
    return df

# each election have his own raf so we will check if the ratio is above that raf or not
def supervisionNeed(df, raf):
    superviseNeeded=[]
    for ratio in df["יחס סופי"] :
        if ratio > raf:
            superviseNeeded.append(1)
        else:
            superviseNeeded.append(0) 
    df["פיקוח"] = superviseNeeded

Features and data explanation:¶

Our data have 1210 rows for the number of settlments. Each data set have row number 1211 which is the sum of the settlments votes for each party, number of population, number of voters, invalid and valid vvotes. We have 3 diffrent data sets, 1 for each election which hold the total amput of the votes for each party and the demoghraphic features for each settlmet. Moreover we created 2 data sets which hold the avg of electin 21+22 and hold the avf of election 21+22+23. the avg is only on the votes per each party. this way we can check what the majority from out population ad voters voted in 3 or 2 diffrent elections.

Each dataset hold the following features:

1) District - each settlement ascribe to diffrent district. In israel there are 7 different.

2) Napa - small area inside the district. each district have number of napas.

3) Settlement form - each city have his own form. In Israel there are number of different forms.

4) settlement religious - We have Jewish, Arabs, durozi and other religious. each settlement have his own.

5) Jewish and others - the number of the Jewish and other religion in spcific settlement.

6) Jewish - the number of the Jewish in spcific settlement.

7) Arabs - the number of the Arabs in spcific settlement.

8) voters - The number from the population who can vote in election

9) voted - the number of the people who voted in te election

10) invalid - the number of voted which invalif from the total amount of voters in the election

11) Valid - valid votes from the entire voters in the election.

# this matrix corellation we took from KAGGLE WEBSITE and we modified to work with our data.
dfVote23 = dfVote23.iloc[:,13:22]

#create the party sizes normalized
party_sizes = dfVote23.sum().div(dfVote23.sum().sum())
#take the biggest parties - the one who pass the bar
major_parties = party_sizes.index[party_sizes>0.01].to_list()
normalized_votes=dfVote23.div(dfVote23.sum(axis=1), axis=0) 

pca=PCA(n_components=2)
major_party_votes=normalized_votes[major_parties]

G=nx.Graph(major_party_votes.corr()>0)
G=nx.relabel_nodes(G,dict(zip(G.nodes(),[x[::-1] for x in major_parties])))
communities=best_partition(G)

community_colors={0:0,1:0.2,2:0.5,3:0.7,4:0.9}
node_coloring=[community_colors[communities[node]] for node in G.nodes()]

nx.pos=nx.fruchterman_reingold_layout(G, dim=2, k=None, pos=None, fixed=None, iterations=5000, weight='weight', scale=1.0, center=None)
nx.draw_networkx(G, cmap=plt.get_cmap('jet'), with_labels=True, node_color=node_coloring,font_size=30)
plt.title('תיוירקיע תוגלפמ - היצלרוק תשר', fontsize=22)
fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(18.5, 10.5)

Question 3 - CLUSTERING¶

  • we will use 2 clusters methods to predict some demographic feature on our data.
    1. we will use K-MEANS to predict the votes in major 20 settlements in israel and which party they vote the most
    2. we will use Hirarhical clustering to check the votes of specific settelments forms.
    3. Assumptions:
      • The largest Party in Israel will me Likud - more settlements voted to Likud party
      • In center and Tel-Aviv districts we think more votes will go to Blue&White party whereas in south district more votes will go to Likud.
      • Arab Settelements votes for Join List Party

K-MEANS¶

In K-Means clustering we wil predic to which party the biggest 30 settlments will vote for and which party district 4 votes the most. In each cluster in the model we will check the biggest 3 parties. Becuse we handling with large amount of data - many settlments without duplication we chose to use K-means. This clustering handle better with large data and we dont care about the miss clusiffication this cluster can do. The K-means is very fast model and his running complexity is low. Moreover, because we have a pre-knowledge available on the settlements, for example what district, what form, religious and more features the k-mean can devide them well. Each settelemnt have his own demoghraphic features and the dataset spread very well.

To check the answer we will use the follwing features: Settlement name and all the parties in the election.

  • Parts from this section code we took from kaggle website - Israeli election

Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • In Hierarchical cluster we took the data set which hold the avg votes from the last 3 elections.
  • Each party column holds the avg from the 3 election. In the data we use, we created new features which holds the party who got the most votes in each settelement and a eature hold the the majority from 3 election voted for this party.
  • In this cluster method we will predict the settelements forms voting. We will take a specific form and try to check and predict which party they vote for.
  • For the specific settelement form we will check how many settelements we have from our enetire datset.
  • We will use the following features: settlement form and the majority voters (בחירות מאוחד)
  • We chose to use hirarchical becuase 'settelemnt form' feature is a small data and Hierarchical clustering preforme well with small data. this cluster is easy to implement.
  • Due to predicting settelements form we dont need to know the K before we doing this cluster method. Due to that, we will gain the privilage to choose which K we want.

Question 6¶

prediction - which settelement need supervision¶

  • Prediction Time: 1 week before election 23
  • Table Time: 1 dayafter the election 23

In this section, after checking adaboost, random forest and meanshift we figured the best model to predict the most aqurate prediction is Decision Tree model.

  • On each election we will check the ration between the number of voters in each settelement with the invalid votes.
  • we will determine the raf for each election and calculate which settelement ratio is under that bar.
  • we will determine the bar by the 250th location settelement. we will tell the goverment the top 250 settelement who need supervision and let them decide which they want to place supervisors. This way we wont give lower number of settelement. Better to give more then less settlments.
  • becuase we have small and large settelement we divided the number of voters by sqrt (שורש) so the largest settelement will get more score then the smaller ones.
  • Train phase: tרain the model on election 21 and check the prediction on election 22. after that we will train again our model on the avg votes data in election 21 + 22. when we finish with this step we will try to predict the supervition on election 23.
  • because we dont have any details on election 23, we will use onnly demographich features.
Workflow:¶

1) Firstly, we figured which features will gain the most in our task. We decided to take: "בזב", "ערבים", "יהודים ואחרים", "דת"

  • becuase we predict a future election results we cant use features that have direct coralletion for number of voters and valin or invalid feature.

2) How to calculate which settelement need suppervition and which dont:

  • To do so, we iterated over our election 21, 22 and election 23 and we gave "1" to suppervition and "0" to none.
  • calculation method: because we have many big citied and after figured out doing % between number of invalid votes and number of voters we missed few settelement because doing % is not accurate enough. Due to that, we decided to do the ratio between invaid votes and sqrt on the number of voters. In this way we will give more score for larger settlement over the small settlements.
  • After classify all the settlements we decided to take the top 250 settelement that have the most ratio.

3) We will try to predict those 250 settlement. We were asked to give our prediction so we will give the comitee 250 settelement and will show them the top 10. In this way we can give them the option to chose which settlements the way to place suppervitions and which not to.

4) To figure which model will predict the most aqurate predictions with our features. We figured we should use decision tree.

5) After finding our best features and model, we will train the Decision Tree model with election 21 data set with the relevant features and test our model with the election 22 data set. after doing that we will train again our model with the 21+22 avg dataset to get better prediction. With this way we will get better and aqurate results to predict in election 23.

6) After we trained and optimized our model we will predict the number of voted to each party in each settlement.

7) We will show the prediction vs. the real supervition in election 23 via a table and confusion matrix.

8) make the conclution over the settlement we predicted need supervision.

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import itertools

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,normalize=False, title='Confusion matrix', cmap="Blues"):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    Source: http://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_confusion_matrix.html
    """
    print(cm)

    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 10))
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title, size = 24)
    plt.colorbar(aspect=4)
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45, size = 14)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes, size = 14)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    
    # Labeling the plot
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt), fontsize = 20,
                 verticalalignment="top",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")
        
    plt.grid(None)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label', size = 18)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label', size = 18)
    
# compare the real supervision vs the prediction
confusion_matrix = confusion_matrix(vote23Inspection.iloc[:,-1], prediction_V23)
plot_confusion_matrix(confusion_matrix, classes = ['No need supervise', 'supervise'], title = 'Supervision - Confusion Matrix')
